573	session-1776284126108	ASSISTANT	Account Takeover (ATO) is a type of fraud in banking where an attacker gains unauthorized access to a user's account and performs fraudulent transactions. This type of fraud is characterized by the following:\n\n- An attacker successfully gains access to a user's account, often through methods such as phishing, where the user unknowingly shares their credentials.\n- Once access is gained, the attacker can perform unauthorized transactions, such as transferring funds or making purchases.\n- ATO attacks often involve sudden location and device changes, as seen in the case scenario where a user login was detected from a new device in a different city followed by a fund transfer.\n\nTo detect and prevent ATO, financial institutions use fraud monitoring systems that analyze transaction patterns, user behavior, geographical anomalies, and transaction frequency and velocity. These systems can trigger alerts or mark transactions as fraudulent based on predefined rules and thresholds. In the case of an ATO, the system may mark the account as FRAUD, terminate the session, and lock the account to prevent further unauthorized transactions. Analysts may then reset credentials, advise customers on phishing risks, and investigate the compromised account.	2026-04-16 11:48:08.555245	adminuser7
