586	session-1776284126108	ASSISTANT	According to the provided search results, fraud is defined as "Unauthorized financial activity". This means any financial transaction that is carried out without the proper authorization or consent of the involved parties. Fraud can take various forms, including transaction fraud, account takeover, card fraud, identity theft, and phishing attacks. Financial institutions use fraud detection systems to identify and prevent such unauthorized activities. These systems analyze transaction patterns, user behavior, geographical anomalies, transaction frequency, and velocity to classify transactions into valid, alert, or fraud categories. Transactions classified as fraud are high-risk and confirmed as fraudulent.	2026-04-16 11:51:54.970692	adminuser7
587	session-1776284126108	USER	fraud detection meaning	2026-04-16 11:52:14.492456	adminuser7
588	session-1776284126108	ASSISTANT	Fraud detection refers to the process of identifying and preventing fraudulent activities in banking systems. It involves the use of rule-based and behavior-based mechanisms to detect suspicious or unauthorized transactions. Financial institutions employ fraud monitoring systems to prevent financial loss, ensure compliance, and protect customer accounts. \n\nFraud detection systems typically analyze transaction patterns, user behavior, geographical anomalies, and transaction frequency and velocity. Transactions are classified into three categories: VALID (normal transactions with no suspicious behavior), ALERT (suspicious transactions requiring further review), and FRAUD (high-risk transactions confirmed as fraudulent).\n\nThe fraud detection process includes several steps, such as alert verification, transaction analysis, customer behavior review, risk score evaluation, and customer contact. The system combines rule-based detection, probabilistic fraud scoring, behavioral analysis, and AI-assisted investigation to detect suspicious transactions in real time, assign a fraud risk score, provide explainable reasoning for decisions, and assist fraud analysts in investigation.\n\nFraud risk scoring assigns a risk score to each transaction based on factors such as transaction amount, frequency, location mismatch, historical behavior, and device/IP anomalies. Transactions with a risk score of 0-30 are considered low risk, 31-70 are considered medium risk (ALERT), and 71-100 are considered high risk (FRAUD).\n\nFraud detection is an essential component of anti-money laundering (AML) guidelines, which ensure financial institutions detect and prevent money laundering. AML principles include customer due diligence (CDD), know your customer (KYC), transaction monitoring, and suspicious activity reporting (SAR). Suspicious transaction indicators may include large amount transfers occurring suddenly, multiple transactions within a short time period, transactions from unusual or distant locations, transactions to newly added accounts, and transactions during unusual hours.	2026-04-16 11:52:16.781318	adminuser7
