1261	session-1776360545839	ASSISTANT	The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) has established comprehensive guidelines to combat fraud in banking systems. Here are the key components of the RBI fraud guidelines:\n\n1. **Fraud Monitoring**: Banks are required to monitor transactions in real-time to detect suspicious patterns and report fraud within defined timelines. They must maintain audit logs for compliance.\n\n2. **Know Your Customer (KYC)**: Banks must verify customer identity through PAN, Aadhaar, address, and mobile/email details. KYC can be Minimum, Full, or require periodic updates.\n\n3. **Anti-Money Laundering (AML)**: AML guidelines ensure the detection of illegal fund flows. Key controls include Customer Due Diligence (CDD), Enhanced Due Diligence (EDD), Transaction Monitoring, and Suspicious Activity Reporting.\n\n4. **Suspicious Transaction Reporting (STR)**: Banks must report large unusual transactions, frequent transfers, and structuring/splitting transactions to the Financial Intelligence Unit (FIU-IND).\n\n5. **Risk-Based Approach**: Customers are categorized as Low, Medium, or High Risk. High-risk customers require enhanced monitoring and additional verification.\n\n6. **Transaction Monitoring Rules**: Banks must monitor high-value transactions, frequent transactions, cross-border transfers, and new beneficiaries.\n\n7. **Account Freezing Guidelines**: Accounts can be blocked if fraud is suspected, there is an AML violation, or per regulatory instruction.\n\nThese guidelines are designed to prevent financial loss, ensure compliance, and protect customer accounts. Banks are also required to review flagged transactions, verify customer identity, analyze transaction history, and take appropriate action.	2026-04-17 00:30:01.208809	deepak
