1118	session-1776349720514	ASSISTANT	The Fraud Investigation Standard Operating Procedure (SOP) typically involves the following steps:\n\n1. **Alert Verification**: Confirm that the fraud alert generated by the monitoring system corresponds to a valid transaction event.\n\n2. **Transaction Analysis**: Review transaction attributes such as time, location, merchant category, and amount.\n\n3. **Customer Behaviour Review**: Compare the suspicious transaction with historical transaction patterns of the customer.\n\n4. **Risk Score Evaluation**: Check the fraud risk score assigned by the monitoring system and determine whether the alert exceeds defined risk thresholds.\n\n5. **Customer Contact**: If necessary, contact the customer to verify whether the transaction was authorized.\n\n6. **Case Resolution**: Decide whether to mark the alert as false positive, escalate for further investigation, or block the associated account.\n\nAdditional steps may include:\n\n- **Review flagged transactions**: Verify customer identity, analyze transaction history, take action (block/monitor), and document findings.\n\n- **Compliance & Reporting**: Report suspicious transactions, maintain audit logs, and follow regulatory guidelines (RBI, FATF).\n\n- **Fraud Detection Rules**: Transactions are classified into three categories: VALID, ALERT, and FRAUD.\n\n- **Fraud Patterns**: Common fraud patterns include rapid transactions, round amount transactions, repeated failed attempts, cross-border anomalies, same sender to multiple receivers.\n\n- **Fraud Prevention Techniques**: Multi-factor authentication (MFA), real-time transaction monitoring, AI-based anomaly detection, behavioral biometrics, device fingerprinting.\n\n- **Analyst Guidelines**: Fraud analysts should review flagged transactions, verify customer identity, analyze transaction history, take action (block/monitor), and document findings.	2026-04-16 20:20:50.656985	deepak
